Preheat a well-oiled #grill{} to medium-high heat. Wash and dry produce.

> TIP: If using a grill pan, you'll heat it in step 5.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into 1/2-inch-thick wedges. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Drain @corn{13.4%ounce}. Halve @grape tomatoes{4%ounce} lengthwise.

Place potatoes in a large #microwave-safe bowl{}; cover tightly with #plastic wrap{}. Microwave until tender, ~{5%minutes}. Uncover; drain any excess water. Toss with a drizzle of @oil{}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{4%tablespoon}, @hot sauce{1%teaspoon}, half the @Dijon mustard{2%teaspoon}, half the @paprika{1%teaspoon}, and @sugar{1/4%teaspoon}. Season with salt and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @shelled edamame{4%ounce}, scallion whites, half the corn, and a pinch of salt. Cook, stirring, until lightly browned, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add @veggie stock concentrate{2}, half the @Cajun spice blend{1%tablespoon}, and 1/4 cup water. Cook, stirring, until tender and water has evaporated, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in tomatoes and @butter{1%tablespoon}; season with salt and pepper. Remove from heat; cover to keep warm.

Pat @barramundi{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; drizzle with oil and rub to coat. Season all over with remaining Cajun spice blend, salt, and pepper.

Place half the @chili lime butter{2%tablespoon} in a second small microwave-safe bowl. Microwave until melted, ~{30%seconds}.

Rinse @shrimp{10%ounce} under cold water; pat dry with paper towels. Place in the center of a large piece of #foil{}; toss with melted chili lime butter, @garlic powder{2%teaspoon}, and a pinch of salt and pepper. Cinch into a packet.

> PAN ALTERNATIVE: Skip melting the chili lime butter and tossing shrimp in the foil packet. (You'll cook the shrimp in step 5.)

Add potatoes, cut sides down, and shrimp packet to grill. Grill potatoes, ~{3-5%minutes}. Grill shrimp, ~{8-10%minutes}. Grill barramundi, ~{4-6%minutes} per side.

> TIP: For a grill pan, lightly oil; heat over medium high. Work in batches. If potatoes are too small, line grill with foil. Grills can vary.

Remove from heat. Return potatoes to bowl; toss with remaining chili lime butter and cover.

> PAN ALTERNATIVE: Cook potatoes in a large oiled pan over medium-high heat, 3-5 minutes. Return to bowl; toss with half the chili lime butter. Wipe out pan. Cook barramundi in oil, 4-6 minutes per side. In a second oiled pan over medium-high heat, cook shrimp with garlic powder, salt, and pepper, 3-4 minutes. Stir in remaining chili lime butter.

Stir half the scallion greens into pan with succotash.

Divide shrimp, barramundi, potatoes, and succotash between plates. Top shrimp and barramundi with remaining scallion greens. Serve with remoulade on the side for dipping.

> Serve the savory hot-sauce remoulade on the side for dipping or drizzle it over your fish for an extra spicy kick.
> Remoulade recipe: mayonnaise, hot sauce, mustard, paprika, and sugar mixed to taste.